on, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"1130–before 1175":"1130–before 1175","1134–Female":"1134–Deceased","1152–1182":"1152–1182","1154–Male":"1154–Deceased","1130–1175":"1130–1175","1134":"1134","1154":"1154","before 1175":"before 1175","1175":"1175","1130":"1130","1152":"1152","1151":"1151","1182":"1182","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Rillington, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rillington, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Rillington, Yorkshire, England":"Rillington, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Rilston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Leicestershire):","habitational name either from Rolleston (Leicestershire, Nottinghamshire, Staffordshire) and perhaps Rowston (Lincolnshire), Rolston (or Rowlston) in Mappleton (East Yorkshire), or from Rollestone in Upton Pyne, or Rolstone Barton in Morchard Bishop (both in Devon), or Rollestone (Wiltshire), and perhaps Rowlestone (Herefordshire) or Rolstone in Banwell (Somerset). The placenames have various etymological origins, though most are named with the Middle English personal name <i>Rolf</i> or the Old Norse personal name <i>Hrólfr</i> + Middle English <i>toun</i> ‘town, settlement’, Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. See   Rolfe  .","variant of   Rollison  , shortened to <i>Rolleson</i> and altered by the addition of an intrusive <i>-t-</i>, as though it were a habitational name in <i>-ston</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Roulston","meanings":["English (Leicestershire and Nottinghamshire): variant of   Rolston  ."]},{"name":"Rolfe","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, from the Middle English and Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Rolf</i>, <i>Roulf</i>, <i>Rou</i>, <i>Roul</i>, <i>Rouf</i>, <i>Rof</i>. Its usual derivation is from Old Norse <i>Hrólfr</i>, <i>Rolf</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’, and occasionally from ancient Germanic <i>Rodulf</i>, of the same origin as <i>Hrólfr</i> (earlier <i>Hróthúlfr</i>) but in a West Frankish form, which the Scandinavian Normans occasionally used. The name was also common in Normandy where it became Old French <i>Roul</i>, <i>Rou</i>, often Latinized as <i>Rollo</i>. See   Ralph   and compare   Rowe  ,   Dow  , and   Rowson  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Rilston was born in 1130, in Yorkshire, England. He married F Rilston in 1151, in Rillington, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died before 